a, Hannig takes the reader deep into a world inside hospital walls, where women recount stories of loss and belonging, shame and delight. As she chronicles the lived experiences of fistula patients in clinical treatment, Hannig explores the danger of labeling “culture” the culprit, showing how this common argument ignores the larger problem of insufficient medical access in rural Africa. Beyond Surgery portrays the complex social outcomes of surgery in an effort to deepen our understanding of medical missions in Africa, expose cultural biases, and clear the path toward more effective ways of delivering care to those who need it most.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFistula, Vesico-vaginalxHospitalszEthiopiazʼAmāra kelel. 0aFistula, Vesico-vaginalxReligious aspectsxYaʼItyop̣yā ʼortodoks tawāḥedo béta kerestiyān. 0aFistula, Vesico-vaginalxSocial aspectsxEthiopia. 0aFistula, Vesico-vaginalxSocial aspectszEthiopia. 0aFistula, Vesico-vaginalxTreatmentxEthiopia. 0aFistula, Vesico-vaginalxTreatmentzEthiopia. 0aMedical anthropologyxEthiopia. 0aMedical anthropologyzEthiopia. 0aWomen patientszEthiopiazʼAmāra kelel. 0aWomen's hospitalsxEthiopia. 0aWomen's hospitalszEthiopiazʼAmāra kelel. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aChristianity.  aEthiopia.  aWestern aid.  abiomedicine.  aculture.  aethnography.  ahospital.  amaternal health.  aobstetric fistula.  astructural violence.  asurgery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226457321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226457321/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles